elements.content: Two new dicyanamido-bridged polymeric complexes of manganese(II), [Mn(dca)2(pic)2] n 1 and [Mn(dca)2(biim)] n 2 (dca = dicyanamide, pic = 4-picoline, biim = 2,2‘-biimidazole), have been synthesized and characterized by X-ray single-crystal structure. Complex 1 forms a one-dimensional chain where [Mn(II)(pic)2] units are connected by double dca bridging ligands. These 1D chains interact through face-to-face π stacking of the 4-picoline pyridine rings extending the dimensionality to a 2D supramolecular network. In complex 2 [Mn(II)(dca)(biim)] units are connected by a single dca bridging ligand to form a 1D chain of five coordinated Mn(II). The pentacoordination of Mn(II) is achieved by the bifurcated H-bond occurring between the terminal N atom of pendant dca and the two NH fragments of ligated 2,2‘-biimidazole. These chains are interlocked by cooperative hydrogen bonding and π−π interactions to generate (4,4) nets, which are 2-fold interpenetrated to form an interwoven 2D sheet. The variable temperature magnetic susceptibility measurements were performed, and the study reveals an antiferromagnetic interaction between the metal centers.

The choice of a suitable coligand can control the coordination geometry of the metal ion, sometimes forming a coordinatively unsaturated metal center. Introduction

One of the possible strategies to improve the selectivity toward the reactivity of coordination polymers is to synthesize inorganic-organic hybrid frameworks with different metal coordination environments, as has been observed in some metalloenzymes. The choice of a suitable coligand can control the coordination geometry of the metal ion, sometimes forming a coordinatively unsaturated metal center. Such coordinatively unsaturated, electron-rich transition metal complexes have proven to be powerful species for small molecule activation and functionalization. During past decades dicyanamide was extensively used with some organic coligand to design coordination polymers. Recently, a comprehensive study of the structural and magnetic properties of dicyanamido-bridged coordination polymers has been reported, which stimulates the interest toward this particular bridging ligand. The structural characterizations of several ternary systems of general formula [M(dca)2L2] n , where M = Mn(II), Cu(II), Cd(II) and L = pyridine (or its substituted derivatives), or L2 = chelating ligand like 1,10-phenanthroline (phen), 2,2‘-bipyridine (bipy), have been reported. These polymers are formed by double bridging dca anions, -M(dca)2M-, having a linear topology with trans positioned monodentate N donor ligands6-10 or a zigzag arrangement in the case of bidentate chelating phen or bipy ligands. Alternatively, pentacoordinated Cu(II) and Cd(II) species, with chelating ligands, exhibit single end-to-end bridging dca with a second dca group pendant from the chain. A few examples of 2D layered structures have also been described. With Lewis base ancillary ligands [py, 2,2‘-bipy, 4,4‘-bipy, pyrazine, 4CN-py, 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane, etc.], and only bidentate μ1,5-dca, long range ordering is generally not observed. In this case the coupling is almost exclusively antiferromagnetic and weak.

elements.content: All the above-mentioned literature is concerned with the tuning of topology of complexes using the coordination linkage of dca. During recent years we are engaged in understanding the role of weak interactions in controlling the topology or geometry of a molecule. With these views, we have tried to elucidate how the structure of a coligand can act as an effective tool in controlling the structure, hence the magnetic properties, of a metal−dca system. Here we wish to report about the structural characterization and magnetic properties of two new Mn−dca coordination polymers, [Mn(dca)2(pic)2] n 1 and [Mn(dca)2(biim)] n 2, having different ancillary ligands, namely, 4-picoline (pic) and 2,2‘-biimidazole (biim). 4-Picoline is an aromatic ring containing monodentate ligand, and aromatic 2,2‘-biimidazole possesses exclusive properties as they can be coordinated to metal centers as well as can act as a donor in hydrogen bonding interactions (Scheme ).

elements.content: Physical Measurements. Elemental analyses (carbon, hydrogen, and nitrogen) were performed using a Perkin-Elmer 240C elemental analyzer. Correction for sample holder was made by previous calibration, and diamagnetic corrections were estimated from Pascal's Tables.

elements.content: Synthesis of [Mn(dca) 2 (pic) 2 ] n (1). An aqueous solution (5 mL) of MnCl2·4H2O (1 mmol, 0.197 g) was mixed with 5 mL of methanolic solution of 4-methylpyridine (2 mmol, 0.186 g) with constant stirring for about 10 min. The resulting clear mixture was mixed with an aqueous solution (5 mL) of sodium dicyanamide (2 mmol, 0.178 g) with continuous stirring for 2 h. Finally it was filtered and the filtrate was kept in a CaCl2 desiccator. The colorless single crystals, suitable for X-ray diffraction, were obtained from the filtrate after a few days. Yield:  88%. elements.content: Crystallographic Data Collection and Refinement. A suitable single crystal of the complex 1 was mounted on a Bruker SMART CCD diffractometer equipped with graphite monochromated Mo Kα (λ = 0.71073 Å) radiation. The intensity data were corrected for Lorentz and polarization effects, and an empirical absorption correction were also employed using the SAINT18 program. The single-crystal data collection of complex 2 was carried out at 293(3) K on a Nonius DIP-1030H system with Mo Kα (λ = 0.71073 Å) radiation. Cell refinement, indexing, and scaling of the data sets were carried out using the programs Mosflm19 and Scala. Both the structures were solved by Patterson syntheses and followed by successive Fourier and difference Fourier syntheses. Full matrix least squares refinements on F 2 were carried out for both cases using SHELXL-9720 with anisotropic displacement parameters for all non-hydrogen atoms. Data collection and structure refinement parameters are given in Table . All calculations were carried out using SHELXL 97, SHELXS 97, PLATON 99, ORTEP-32, and the WinGX system, Ver. 1.64. Crystal Structure Description of Complex 1. X-ray structure determination reveals that complex 1 is made up of [Mn(II)(pic)2] units bridged doubly by μ1,5-dca ligands to form a 1D chain running along c-axis with metals separated by 7.457(1) Å. The ORTEP drawing of a part of the chain with the atom labeling scheme is shown in Figure . Here the Mn(II) ion, located on a center of symmetry, exhibits an octahedral coordination sphere involving four nitrile nitrogens and two 4-picoline nitrogen donors in trans position. The Mn−N(nitrile) bond distances (Table ) of 2.215(3) and 2.221(3) Å are slightly shorter than that involving the picoline, of 2.260(3) Å, but all values are comparable to those found in the pyridine derivatives. The intermetallic distance is closely comparable to those observed in the pyridine, and in the imidazole25 derivatives of 7.540, 7.521, and 7.529 Å, respectively. It is worthy of note that in the linear [Mn(dca)2(bpe)] n (bpe = (1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane) polymer14b with metals bridged by two dicyanamide anions and a bpe ligand, a considerably shorter intermetallic distance of 7.296 Å was achieved.

Crystal Structure Description of Complex 2. X-ray crystallographic analysis reveals that complex 2 is made up of [Mn(dca)(biim)] units bridged singly by μ1,5-dca ligands to form a 1D chain propagating along the a-axis. The ORTEP drawing of part of the chain with the atom labeling scheme is shown in Figure . The dca ligands bound to the metal center are of two types:  one is end-to-end bridging, and the other is pendant from the chain. It is worthy of note that a single bridging dca between two metal centers is quite unusual. The five coordination environment of manganese atoms is satisfied through a chelating biim ligand, two nitrile N donors from bridging dicyanamide, and one nitrile N atom from the monofunctional dicyanamide ligand. Here the five coordinated Mn(II) shows a geometry which is more inclined to square pyramidal than trigonal bipyramidal with an Addison parameter27 of 0.13. The Mn−N(dca) bond distances fall in a range from 2.154(3) to 2.177(3) Å, with Mn−N(nitrile) bond angles within 153.1(2)−172.6(2)° (Table ). These values are closely comparable to those detected in other dicyanamide bridging Mn(II) compounds. The Mn−N(biim) bond distances of 2.275(2) and 2.226(2) Å appear slightly different, although the mean value is comparable to those measured in the Mn(bipy)2(dca)2 for the chelating ligand. The imidazole rings are virtually coplanar (tilt angle of 2°) with a chelating angle of 75.13(8)°. The Mn−Mn separation along the chain is 7.549(3) Å (a-axis), in close agreement with distances of 7.541 and 7.512 Å observed in the two structural characterizations of Mn(bipy)2(dca)2 6,8 comprising −Mn(dca)2Mn− polymers with double end-to-end bridging dca anions.

elements.content: Magnetic Properties. In a very recent review, a comprehensive study of the structural and magnetic data of coordination polymers containing the dicyanamide bridging ligand has been reported. From this review, a classification of these compounds is given. For example, the most important series (from a magnetic point of view) is the called “rutile-like” complexes of formula [M(dca)2] [M = V(II), Cr(II), Mn(II), Fe(II), Co(II), Ni(II)] which show magnetic ordering. They are ferromagnets for M = Co(II) and Ni(II) below 9 and 21 K, respectively, and weak (canted) ferromagnets for M = Cr(II), Mn(II), and Fe(II), below 47, 16, and 19 K, respectively. Recently it has been postulated that even the [Cu(dca)2] presents ferromagnetic ordering. Significantly, tridentate dca (μ3-dca + μ1,5-dca) is present in all of these structures, allowing access to M−(dca)−M magnetic exchange pathways. In contrast, with an ancillary Lewis base ligand, L (such as py, 2,2‘-bipy, 4,4‘-bipy, pyrazine, 4CN-py, 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane, etc.), and the presence of only bidentate μ1,5-dca, long range ordering is not observed. In this case the coupling is almost exclusively antiferromagnetic and weak. The ferromagnetic coupling in polynuclear complexes with μ1,5-dicyanamide bridging ligand is very rare, and it has been attributed to accidental orthogonality between the magnetic orbitals. Escuer et al. theoretically predicted the possibility of small ferromagnetic coupling in Ni(II)−dca systems.

elements.content: Focusing our interest in magnetic properties of Mn(II)−dca complexes, chains formed by two bridging μ1,5-dca ligands per metal are much more common than those having only one per metal. Such chains with a linear geometry (i.e. a trans arrangement of terminal ligands) are particularly common with monodentate ligands. For example, the structures of [Mn(py)2(μ-dca)2] and several pyridine derivatives are typical for this type of system. The metal ions are bridged by four equatorial dca ligands into a linear chain; each pair of adjacent metal ions is connected by a pair of dca ligands. The chains pack in an interdigitated fashion, such that the terminal pyridine ligands are in a π-stacked arrangement. With bidentate ligands (i.e. 2,2‘-bpy) a few double-dca chains have been reported to date, where necessarily the cis arrangement of the terminal ligands will also generate the same chain geometry. One example of this rare case is [Mn(bpy)(μ-dca)2]6,8 (isomorphous with the Cd complex). Weak intrachain antiferromagnetic coupling is observed in all of them. Following this general trend, complex 1, with monodentate terminal ligands, presents the typical double cis-dca one-dimensional chain geometry, whereas 2, with pentacoordinated manganese ions and a chelating terminal ligand, presents a unique geometry that can be considered as a new dca chain with only one dca bridging ligand.

elements.content: Magnetic Studies of the Complexes. Plots of χM T and χM (inset) vs T for complex 1 are shown in Figure . Taking into consideration the one-dimensional structure, magnetic data are taken for one manganese ion. χM T starts at 4.26 cm3 mol-1 K for 1 at 300 K, which is the typical value for one isolated Mn(II) ion (g = 2.00). This value is almost constant up to 100 K, decreasing rapidly to 2.04 cm3 mol-1 K at 3 K. This feature is indicative of weak antiferromagnetic coupling among the Mn(II) ions. Although similar, the shape of the χM T and mainly χM curve for complex 2 is slightly different (Figure ). χM T starts at 4.40 cm3 mol-1 K at 300 K, which is the typical value for one isolated Mn(II) ion (g = 2.00). This value is almost constant up to 100 K, decreasing rapidly to 0.08 cm3 mol-1 K at 2 K. The main difference is the shape of the χM curve at very low temperature:  only in complex 2 there is a clear maximum at 8 K with a very pronounced decrease to 2 K. In this type of one-dimensional Mn(II) system (S = 5/2) it is possible to fit the experimental susceptibility data to the formula given by Fisher for a model with classical spin. The best-fit parameters were J = −0.33 cm-1, g = 1.99, and R = 2.7 × 10-3 for complex 1 and J = −0.74 cm-1, g = 2.02, and R = 2.1 × 10-2 for complex 2. J and g values for 1 are typical for this type of Mn−dca complex. However, for 2, J and g seem to be fine but R is the worst. All attempts to fit the data of 2 considering the molecular field model (assuming intermolecular J ‘ values) failed, undoubtedly due to the small value of J. It is difficult to explain this behavior, but the structure of complex 2 is certainly responsible for this. As indicated in the structural part, the Mn(II) in 2 is pentacoordinated, giving a “simple” one-dimensional system. The occurrence of such coordination geometry for Mn(II) is very rare. In this case the formula of Fisher would not be completely valid owing to the complicated π−π stacking and the hydrogen bonds. However, the most important feature, difficult to elucidate quantitatively, is the stronger antiferromagnetic coupling observed in 2 (maximum of χM clearly visible), with only one dca bridge, with respect to complex 1, with double dca bridges. Furthermore, the tendency of χM T approaching to 0 in 2 corroborates this difference with regard to complex 1. Thus, the magnetic pathway not only occurs through the dca bridges but also may take place through the three-dimensional noncovalent (supramolecular) packing. Other complexes with only one dca bridge are to be prepared in order to corroborate this hypothesis.

Conclusions

The crystal structures of the two Mn-dca complexes here reported show coordination 1D polymers extended to supramolecular 2D sheet by π-π interactions only in the case of complex 1 and by a cooperative H-bonding scheme and π-π interactions in the case of 2. In the latter complex the Mn atoms are five coordinated and the unsaturated coordination sphere is created mainly by H-bonding. Manipulations of the covalent bond are extensively used in structure design, but the role of a directed H-bond to control the coordination environment is quite unprecedented. This coordinatively unsaturated metal center is well accessible due to the lower energy of H-bonding, and its access may be helpful for potential use in catalytic reactions. We haunted the answers to the most important questions pertinent to the result of the experiment. Can we engineer the interrelated interactions to dominate a particular preassigned interaction over the others? Can the bifurcated or higher order designing of H-bonding compete over covalent bonds? At least, this is a unique example where weak interactions throw a challenge to the classical covalent bond saying, "we can".

Synthesis of [Mn(dca) 2 (pic) 2 ] n (1). An aqueous solution (5 mL) of MnCl2·4H2O (1 mmol, 0.197 g) was mixed with 5 mL of methanolic solution of 4-methylpyridine (2 mmol, 0.186 g) with constant stirring for about 10 min. The resulting clear mixture was mixed with an aqueous solution (5 mL) of sodium dicyanamide (2 mmol, 0.178 g) with continuous stirring for 2 h. Finally it was filtered and the filtrate was kept in a CaCl2 desiccator. The colorless single crystals, suitable for X-ray diffraction, were obtained from the filtrate after a few days. Yield:  88%. Anal. Calcd for C16H14MnN8:  C, 51.43; H, 3.75; N, 30.00 (%). Found:  C, 51.48; H, 3.73; N, 29.98 (%). IR data:  ν = 3410 (br), 1580 (s), 1448 (m), 1256 (w), 952 (w), 809 (m), 692 (m) cm-1.

Synthesis of [Mn(dca) 2 (biim)] n (2). To a boiling methanolic suspension of 2,2‘-biimidazole (biim) (2 mmol, 0.268 g) was added a methanolic solution (5 mL) of MnCl2· 4H2O (1 mmol, 0.197 g) with constant stirring. An aqueous solution (4 mL) of sodium dicyanamide (2 mmol, 0.178 g) was added to the above mixture, and then the mixture was refluxed for 12 h. After cooling it was filtered and the filtrate was kept in a CaCl2 desiccator. Deep brown single crystals suitable for X-ray diffraction were obtained from the filtrate after a few weeks. Yield:  68%. Anal. Calcd for C10H6MnN10:  C, 37.36; H, 1.87; N, 43.59 (%). Found:  C, 37.11; H, 1.85; N, 43.38 (%). IR data:  ν = 3431 (br), 2156 (s), 1585 (s), 1481 (m), 1411 (m), 1338 (w), 1319 (w), 1220 (w), 1010 (w), 812 (m), 709 (s) cm-1.
